---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Control Model Training";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout
  title={`${title} | Yaw Control`}
  lang="en"
  prevHref={`${base}/en/environment/`}
  prevLabel="Environment"
  nextHref={`${base}/en/yaw_estimation`}
  nextLabel="Yaw Estimation"
>
  <article class="detail-page">
    <h1>{title}</h1>

    <p>
      A reinforcement learning model was trained in a physics-based control
      environment to generate a policy that controls the payload to the target
      yaw angle.
    </p>

    <nav class="page-nav">
      <div class="page-nav-row">
        <a href="#flow">Training Workflow</a>
        <a href="#physics">Physics Simulation</a>
        <a href="#training">Reinforcement Learning</a>
        <a href="#targets">Training Targets</a>
        <a href="#inference">Using the Trained Model</a>
        <a href="#chart">How to Read the Evaluation Charts</a>
      </div>
      <div class="page-nav-row">
        <span>Evaluation Results:</span>
        <a href="#hsteel">HSteel</a>
        <a href="#plate">Plate</a>
        <a href="#truss">Truss</a>
      </div>
    </nav>    

    <section id="flow" class="content-section">
      <h2>Training Workflow</h2>
      <p>
        The training script executes the control environment together with the
        reinforcement learning algorithm to generate a control policy.
        The trained model is then loaded by the inference script to control the
        payload, and the results are visualized and evaluated.
      </p>

      <figure class="flow-figure">
        <img
          src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/control_model_flow_en.png`}
          alt="Workflow from model training to inference and evaluation"
        />
        <figcaption>
          Workflow from model training to inference and evaluation.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section id="physics" class="content-section">
      <h2>Physics Simulation</h2>
      <p>
        The physics engine simulates the motion of the payload, suspension ropes,
        control unit, and crane. To reproduce realistic suspended-load behavior,
        the simulation considers not only the payload geometry and mass, but also
        rope constraints, wind disturbances, and thruster forces.
      </p>
      <div class="physics-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="item-title">Gravity</span>
          <span>Applied to the payload and control unit</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="item-title">Rope Constraints</span>
          <span>Connect the crane, control unit, and payload</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="item-title">Moment of Inertia</span>
          <span>Determined by the payload geometry and mass</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="item-title">Wind Disturbance</span>
          <span>Applies external forces to the payload</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="item-title">Thruster Forces</span>
          <span>Applied from the control model output</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="item-title">Collision Detection</span>
          <span>Calculates contact between structures</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="training" class="content-section">
      <h2>Reinforcement Learning</h2>
      <p>
        A reinforcement learning model was used to generate continuous control
        outputs. The model receives the state of the payload and control unit as
        input and computes the thrust commands for the four thrusters.      
      </p>
      <div class="learning-flow" aria-label="Reinforcement learning control flow">
        <div>
          <strong>State</strong>
          <span>Yaw angle, angular velocity, etc.</span>
        </div>
        <span class="learning-flow__arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        <div>
          <strong>RL Model</strong>
          <span>Infers control outputs</span>
        </div>
        <span class="learning-flow__arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Action</strong>
          <span>Four thruster commands</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        The model is trained to rotate the payload to the target yaw angle and
        maintain its orientation after reaching the target. Under wind
        disturbances, it also learns how to generate thruster commands that
        compensate for external forces.      
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="targets" class="content-section">
      <h2>Training Targets</h2>
      <p>
        The HSteel, Plate, and Truss payloads differ in geometry, mass, rope
        attachment points, and rotational characteristics. Therefore, separate
        control models were trained for each payload under different disturbance
        conditions.      
      </p>
      <div class="model-grid">
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/hsteel_learning.png`}
            alt="Training environment for the HSteel payload"
          />
          <figcaption>
            <span class="figure-title">HSteel (2-Point Suspension)</span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/plate_learning.png`}
            alt="Training environment for the Plate payload"
          />
          <figcaption>
            <span class="figure-title">PPlate (4-Point Suspension)</span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/truss_learning.png`}
            alt="Training environment for the Truss payload"
          />
          <figcaption>
            <span class="figure-title">Truss (4-Point Suspension)</span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
      <p class="note">
        The same reinforcement learning method was applied to all payloads to
        evaluate its adaptability under different payload configurations and
        disturbance conditions.      
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="inference" class="content-section">
      <h2>Using the Trained Model</h2>
      <p>
        After training, only the trained model is extracted and loaded by the
        inference script. During control, the current state is provided to the
        model at fixed intervals, and the computed thruster commands are held until
        the next control cycle.      
      </p>
      <div class="inference-flow" aria-label="学習済みモデルを利用した制御の流れ">
        <div>
          <strong>Control Environment</strong>
          <span>Provides the current state</span>
        </div>
        <span class="inference-flow__arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Trained Model</strong>
          <span>Computes thruster commands</span>
        </div>
        <span class="inference-flow__arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Physics Engine</strong>
          <span>Applies the thrust</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        The inference results are saved as CSV files and visualized as evaluation
        charts showing the payload yaw angle and the thrust history of each
        thruster.      
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="chart" class="content-section">
      <h2>How to Read the Evaluation Charts</h2>
      <p>
        Control performance is evaluated by comparing the payload yaw angle
        without thruster control (Baseline) and with reinforcement learning
        control (Control), together with the thrust history of each thruster.      
      </p>
      <div class="chart-layout">
        <figure class="chart-figure">
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/chart_overview.png`}
            alt="Overview of the evaluation charts"
          />
        </figure>
        <div class="chart-description">
          <section>
            <h3>Payload / Disturbance</h3>
            <p>
              The payload type and disturbance condition are shown at the top of
              each chart.            
            </p>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h3>Baseline</h3>
            <p>
              The payload yaw angle without thruster control.
              The red dashed line indicates the target yaw angle, and the blue line
              shows the payload yaw angle.            
            </p>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h3>Control</h3>
            <p>
              The control result generated by the reinforcement learning model.
              The chart shows how quickly the payload reaches the target yaw angle
              and how well it maintains the desired orientation afterward.            
            </p>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h3>Thruster Force Heatmap</h3>
            <p>
              The thrust history of the four thrusters.
              Yellow indicates higher thrust, while purple indicates lower thrust.            
            </p>
          </section>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="hsteel" class="content-section">
      <h2>HSteel: 2-Point Suspension</h2>
      <p>
        HSteel is suspended by two ropes. The control performance was evaluated
        under three disturbance conditions: no wind, one-directional wind, and
        Two-Directional Wind.      
      </p>

      <!-- X0Y0 -->
      <div class="result-primary">
        <figure class="payload-image">
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/hsteel_learning.png`}
            alt="HSteel with 2-point suspension"
          />
          <figcaption>HSteel (2-Point Suspension)</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <div class="result-chart">
          <h3>X0Y0 (No Wind)</h3>        
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target orientation in approximately 10 seconds
            and then maintains a yaw angle close to 90°.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/HSteel_X0Y0.png`}
              alt="HSteel X0Y0"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller maintains the
            orientation with intermittent thrust, primarily using Thruster T3 near
            its maximum output.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- X1Y0 / X1Y1 -->
      <div class="result-grid">
        <article>
          <h3>X1Y0 (One-Directional Wind)</h3>
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target orientation in approximately 10 seconds
            and remains close to 90° thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/HSteel_X1Y0.png`}
              alt="HSteel X1Y0"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller primarily uses
            Thrusters T1 and T2 near their maximum output.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>X1Y1 (Two-Directional Wind)</h3>          
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target orientation in approximately 10 seconds
            and remains close to 90° thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/HSteel_X1Y1.png`}
              alt="HSteel X1Y1"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller uses Thrusters T1,
            T2, and T4, with T2 operating near its maximum output most of the time.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="plate" class="content-section">
      <h2>Plate: 4-Point Suspension</h2>      
      <p>
        The Plate payload is suspended by four ropes. The control performance was
        evaluated under three disturbance conditions: no wind, one-directional
        wind, and two-directional wind.
      </p>

      <!-- X0Y0 -->
      <div class="result-primary">
        <figure class="payload-image">
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/plate_learning.png`}
            alt="Plate with 4-point suspension"
          />
          <figcaption>Plate (4-Point Suspension)</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <div class="result-chart">
          <h3>X0Y0 (No Wind)</h3>
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target yaw angle in approximately 13 seconds
            and maintains it thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/Plate_X0Y0.png`}
              alt="Plate X0Y0"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller primarily uses
            Thrusters T2 and T3 near their maximum output.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- X1Y0 / X1Y1 -->
      <div class="result-grid">
        <article>
          <h3>X1Y0 (One-Directional Wind)</h3>          
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target yaw angle in approximately 13 seconds
            and maintains it thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/Plate_X1Y0.png`}
              alt="Plate X1Y0"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller primarily uses
            Thrusters T1, T3, and T4, with T3 operating near its maximum output.
          </p>
          <p>
            Similar thruster control behavior is observed under both X1Y0 and
            X1Y1 disturbance conditions.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>X1Y1 (Two-Directional Wind)</h3>          
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target yaw angle in approximately 13 seconds
            and maintains it thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/Plate_X1Y1.png`}
              alt="Plate X1Y1"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller primarily uses
            Thrusters T1, T3, and T4, with T3 operating near its maximum output.
          </p>
          <p>
            Similar thruster control behavior is observed under both X1Y0 and
            X1Y1 disturbance conditions.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="truss" class="content-section">
      <h2>Truss: 4-Point Suspension</h2>      
      <p>
        The Truss payload is suspended by four ropes. The control performance was
        evaluated under three disturbance conditions: no wind, one-directional
        wind, and two-directional wind.
      </p>

      <!-- X0Y0 -->
      <div class="result-primary">
        <figure class="payload-image">
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/truss_learning.png`}
            alt="Truss with 4-point suspension"
          />
          <figcaption>Truss (4-Point Suspension)</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <div class="result-chart">
          <h3>X0Y0 (No Wind)</h3>          
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target yaw angle in approximately 20 seconds
            and maintains it thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/Truss_X0Y0.png`}
              alt="Turss X0Y0"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, all four thrusters are used, with
            Thruster T3 operating near its maximum output.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- X1Y0 / X1Y1 -->
      <div class="result-grid">
        <article>
          <h3>X1Y0 (One-Directional Wind)</h3>          
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target yaw angle in approximately 20 seconds
            and maintains it thereafter.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/Truss_X1Y0.png`}
              alt="Turss X1Y0"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, the controller primarily uses
            Thruster T4, while the overall thruster output remains relatively low.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>X1Y1 (Two-Directional Wind)</h3>
          <p>
            The payload reaches the target yaw angle in approximately 40 seconds
            and maintains it thereafter.
            <strong>
              This condition required the longest settling time among all evaluation
              cases.
            </strong>
          </p>
          <figure>
            <img
              src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/images/control_model/Truss_X1Y1.png`}
              alt="Turss X1Y1"
            />
          </figure>
          <p class="result-note">
            After reaching the target yaw angle, all four thrusters operate near
            their maximum output.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .detail-page {
    padding: 32px 0 64px;
  }

  .detail-page > h1 {
    margin: 0 0 20px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .detail-page > p {
    margin: 0;
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .page-nav {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 12px;

    margin: 32px 0 56px;
    padding: 16px 0;

    border-top: 1px solid #ddd;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;
  }

  .page-nav-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 6px 18px;
  }

  .page-nav-row span {
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .content-section {
    scroll-margin-top: 32px;
    margin-bottom: 62px;
  }

  .content-section h2 {
    margin: 0 0 20px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .content-section > p {
    margin: 0 0 28px;
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  figure {
    margin: 0;
  }

  img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }

  figcaption {
    margin-top: 12px;
    color: #666;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .figure-title {
    display: block;
    color: #222;
  }

  .flow-figure {
    max-width: 780px;
    margin: 24px auto 0;
  }

  .physics-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    margin-top: 32px;
    border-top: 1px solid #ddd;
    border-left: 1px solid #ddd;
  }

  .physics-grid > div {
    min-height: 112px;
    padding: 20px;
    border-right: 1px solid #ddd;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;
  }

  .physics-grid span {
    display: block;
  }

  .item-title {
    margin-bottom: 8px;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }

  .physics-grid div span:last-child {
    color: #666;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .learning-flow,
  .inference-flow {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr auto 1fr;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 20px;
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 32px auto;
  }

  .learning-flow > div,
  .inference-flow > div {
    padding: 24px 16px;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    border-radius: 10px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .learning-flow strong,
  .learning-flow span,
  .inference-flow strong,
  .inference-flow span {
    display: block;
  }

  .learning-flow strong,
  .inference-flow strong {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .learning-flow div span,
  .inference-flow div span {
    color: #666;
  }

  .learning-flow__arrow,
  .inference-flow__arrow {
    color: #777;
    font-size: 1.4rem;
  }

  .model-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 20px;
    margin-top: 32px;
  }

  .note {
    margin-top: 24px;
    color: #666;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }

  .detail-navigation {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 24px;
    padding-top: 24px;
    border-top: 1px solid #ddd;
  }

  .detail-navigation a {
    color: inherit;
  }

  .chart-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 48px;
    align-items: start;
  }
  .chart-figure {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .chart-description {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 28px;
  }
  .chart-description h3 {
    margin: 0 0 8px;
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .chart-description p {
    margin: 0 0 1px;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .result-primary {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.3fr;
    gap: 40px;
    align-items: start;
    margin: 40px 0 32px;
  }

  .payload-image img {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
  }

  .result-chart h3,
  .result-grid h3 {
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .result-chart p,
  .result-grid p {
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .result-note {
    margin-top: 20px;
  }

  .result-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 48px;
  }

  .result-grid img,
  .result-chart img {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
  }




  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .chart-layout {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .chart-description {
      gap: 20px;
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .detail-page {
      padding-top: 24px;
    }

    .page-nav {
      margin-bottom: 44px;
    }

    .content-section {
      margin-bottom: 56px;
    }

    .physics-grid,
    .model-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .learning-flow,
    .inference-flow {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 12px;
    }

    .learning-flow__arrow,
    .inference-flow__arrow {
      transform: rotate(90deg);
    }

    .detail-navigation {
      flex-direction: column;
    }
  }
</style>